<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?><api:response xmlns:api="http://www.symplectic.co.uk/publications/api"><api:version uri="https://mypublications.shef.ac.uk/" elements-version="6.17.0.4095" schema-version="6.13" product-name="myPublications"/><api:request href="https://mypublications.shef.ac.uk:8091/secure-api/v6.13/publications/1097342"/><api:result><api:object category="publication" id="1097342" last-affected-when="2024-04-30T11:31:46.36+01:00" last-modified-when="2022-12-29T16:22:40.54+00:00" href="https://mypublications.shef.ac.uk:8091/secure-api/v6.13/publications/1097342" created-when="2018-10-17T19:52:19.883+01:00" type-id="5" type-display-name="Journal article" type="journal-article"><api:privacy-level>Public</api:privacy-level><api:privacy-level-locked>false</api:privacy-level-locked><api:ever-approved>true</api:ever-approved><api:reporting-date-1>2018-01-01</api:reporting-date-1><api:allow-type-switching>true</api:allow-type-switching><api:records><api:record format="native" id="4225882" source-id="28" source-name="eprints" source-display-name="White Rose Research Online" id-at-source="155248" last-modified-when="2022-12-29T16:22:40.54+00:00"><api:native><api:field name="abstract" type="text" display-name="Abstract"><api:text>Many datasets are in the form of tables of binned data. Performing regression on these data usually involves either reading off bin heights, ignoring data from neighbouring bins or interpolating between bins thus over or underestimating the true bin integrals.
In this paper we propose an elegant method for performing Gaussian Process (GP) regression given such binned data, allowing one to make probabilistic predictions of the latent function which produced the binned data.
We look at several applications. First, for differentially private regression; second, to make predictions over other integrals; and third when the input regions are irregularly shaped collections of polytopes.
In summary, our method provides an effective way of analysing binned data such that one can use more information from the histogram representation, and thus reconstruct a more useful and precise density for making predictions.</api:text></api:field><api:field name="authors" type="person-list" display-name="Authors"><api:people><api:person><api:links><api:link type="elements/user" id="14971" href="https://mypublications.shef.ac.uk:8091/secure-api/v6.13/users/14971"/></api:links><api:last-name>Smith</api:last-name><api:initials>MT</api:initials><api:first-names>MT</api:first-names><api:separate-first-names><api:first-name>M</api:first-name><api:first-name>T</api:first-name></api:separate-first-names></api:person><api:person><api:last-name>Álvarez</api:last-name><api:initials>MA</api:initials><api:first-names>MA</api:first-names><api:separate-first-names><api:first-name>M</api:first-name><api:first-name>A</api:first-name></api:separate-first-names></api:person><api:person><api:links><api:link type="elements/user" id="3999" href="https://mypublications.shef.ac.uk:8091/secure-api/v6.13/users/3999"/></api:links><api:last-name>Lawrence</api:last-name><api:initials>ND</api:initials><api:first-names>ND</api:first-names><api:separate-first-names><api:first-name>N</api:first-name><api:first-name>D</api:first-name></api:separate-first-names></api:person></api:people></api:field><api:field name="journal" type="text" display-name="Journal"><api:text>arXiv</api:text></api:field><api:field name="notes" type="text" display-name="Other information"><api:text>© 2018 The Author(s). For reuse permissions, please contact the Author(s).</api:text></api:field><api:field name="publication-status" type="text" display-name="Status"><api:text>Submitted</api:text></api:field><api:field name="public-url" type="text" display-name="Public URL"><api:text>https://eprints.whiterose.ac.uk/id/eprint/155248</api:text></api:field><api:field name="publisher-url" type="text" display-name="Link 2"><api:text